      <p p class="descriptionBody col s8 offset-s2">
         The message that is in plain English is called <b>plaintext</b> and the encrypted message is called a <b>ciphertext</b>.
         The plaintext above on right hand side has been encrypted with a transposition cipher.
         The ciphertext is impossible to read the message unless you know know how the decrypt it.
         It is just random letters with no meaning whatsoever.
         Encrypting your written messages is one way to keep them secret from other people, even if they
         get their hands on the encrypted message itself. They won't be able to understand it.
      </p>
      <p class="descriptionBody col s8 offset-s2">
        A <b>cipher</b> is a set of rules for converting between plaintext and ciphertext.
        These rules often use a secret key. This key is called an encryption key.
        The encryption key is the secret to encrypting or decrypting the message.
        Block ciphers may either have one key for both encryption and decryption, in which
        case they’re called shared key, or have separate keys for encryption and
        decryption, in which case they’re called public key or asymmetric.
        <b>Please not that encrypting more than once does not provide additional strength to the cipher for most of these ciphers.</b>
